data.astory:
Kathie and Monte, Matt Vaughan here in Seattle. Very kind words from you two indeed. Ben was a confident and artistic guy, one who adored his family, and was always great with the fans. His influence ran deep in the Seattle music scene. Ben was an artist first. He sold his paintings and painted t-shirts at Pike Place Market during his Skin Yard and early Gruntruck days, if you didn't have a Ben McMillan t-shirt, you hadn't lived in Seattle. Jack Endino and him became friends early on and between the two of them, they influenced a sound that bands would strive for and in many cases, would eventually accomplish, many of course would become very successfull, Soundgarden being the first to come to mind.

Ben was all about bringing people together, he was always wanting to put on a good show and talk to people afterwards. He didn't mind cramped cars, backrooms, and apartments, he felt good and comfortable in those surroundings. The times he did have a tour bus or a big hotel room, you could see the frown come upon his face. It isn't that he didn't think he deserved it, he just felt more claustrophobic in those surroundings, like someone was playing a joke on him. Gruntruck was on the periphery of stardom. I do think there was some bitterness there on why this band and not his, but at the same time, Ben liked being the underdog. Gruntruck weren't like the rest, they commanded respect, but it was also the band that you could have a smart conversation with or talk about monster movies. Ben could be stubborn, not one who budged very easily, but when he was in his element and he knew it was good, you could only shake your head because he was right. During those early 90's, as far as Seattle was concerned, Gruntruck was the truest of em all and Ben made sure of that. I guess that's why Pearl Jam requested Gruntruck to open for them at their first public performance or why Alice In Chains said if Gruntruck isn't on our tour, we don't tour or why the Screaming Trees thought they should be opening for Gruntruck rather than the other way around . Ben was a statesmen and one who personified the Seattle sound, lyrics, and demeanor. There was nothing pretentious about him or any of his comrades in Gruntruck/Skin Yard. If anything, it's why they never reached superstardom and it's also why their fans were so loyal, they wanted Ben and Gruntruck for their own, it was their tribe, their likeness. Ben is above us all, cracking that smile and giving us a wink. A lovely man.
